# CISSP Analogy Map

This file maps CISSP concepts to analogies drawn from YOUR professional background.
The tutor and comprehension skills read this file before every response.

## How to Use This Template

1. Copy this file to `reference/analogy-map.md`
2. For each domain, pick the analogy source that fits YOUR experience
3. Replace the example analogies with ones from your own work
4. The more specific and personal the analogy, the better it sticks

The example column below uses generic IT analogies as placeholders. Replace them
with analogies from whatever you actually do — the system works best when concepts
map to things you have hands-on experience with.

══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
DOMAIN 1: Security and Risk Management → (YOUR BACKGROUND)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

| CISSP Concept                  | Your Analogy                                          |
|-------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Security governance           | Organizational leadership / chain of command           |
| Security policy               | Standard operating procedures in your org              |
| Risk assessment               | Evaluating threats before a major decision             |
| Risk treatment (accept/       | Accept the risk, reduce it, transfer it (insurance),   |
|   mitigate/transfer/avoid)    |   or avoid the activity entirely                       |
| Quantitative risk analysis    | Putting dollar figures on potential losses              |
| Qualitative risk analysis     | Expert judgment + experience (high/medium/low)         |
| ALE = SLE x ARO               | Expected annual loss = damage per event x frequency    |
| Due diligence                 | Research before committing to a decision               |
| Due care                      | Following established procedures during execution      |
| Compliance                    | Audits / inspections / following regulations            |
| Ethics (ISC2 Code of Ethics)  | Professional code of conduct                           |
| BCP (Business Continuity)     | Plan to keep operations running during a disruption    |
| Legal/regulatory requirements | Rules you must follow — consequences for violations    |
| Senior management support     | Leadership buy-in for security initiatives              |

══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
DOMAIN 2: Asset Security → (YOUR BACKGROUND)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

| CISSP Concept                  | Your Analogy                                          |
|-------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Data classification           | Labeling information by sensitivity level              |
| Data ownership (owner/        | Owner = decides policy, custodian = implements it,     |
|   custodian/steward)          |   steward = tracks and catalogs it                     |
| Data retention policy         | How long you keep records before destruction           |
| Data remanence                | Deleted files are recoverable — sanitize properly      |
| Data at rest / in transit /   | Stored on disk / moving over network / loaded in       |
|   in use                      |   application memory                                   |
| Scoping and tailoring         | Adjusting controls to fit your actual environment      |

══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
DOMAIN 3: Security Architecture & Engineering → (YOUR BACKGROUND)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

| CISSP Concept                  | Your Analogy                                          |
|-------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Defense in depth              | Multiple layers of security — no single point of       |
|                               |   failure                                              |
| Security models (Bell-        | Bell-LaPadula = confidentiality (no read up, no write  |
|   LaPadula, Biba, Clark-     |   down). Biba = integrity (no write up, no read down). |
|   Wilson)                     |   Clark-Wilson = integrity via controlled transactions  |
| Trusted Computing Base (TCB)  | The minimal trusted layer everything else depends on   |
| Security perimeter            | Network boundary / segmentation point                  |
| Cryptography (symmetric)      | One shared key — both sides use the same key           |
| Cryptography (asymmetric)     | Key pair — public key shared, private key stays local  |
| Hashing                       | Fingerprint of data — verify integrity, not decrypt    |
| PKI / certificates            | Trust chain — CA vouches for identity via certificates |
| Side-channel attacks          | Extracting info from implementation behavior (timing,  |
|                               |   power usage) rather than breaking the algorithm      |
| Zero trust architecture       | Never trust implicitly — always verify, even inside    |
|                               |   the network                                          |

══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
DOMAIN 4: Communication & Network Security → (YOUR BACKGROUND)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

| CISSP Concept                  | Your Analogy                                          |
|-------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| OSI model                     | 7-layer networking reference model                     |
| Firewalls (stateful/          | Stateful tracks connection state; stateless checks     |
|   stateless)                  |   each packet independently                            |
| Network segmentation          | Dividing the network into isolated zones               |
| VPN                           | Encrypted tunnel over an untrusted network             |
| TLS/SSL                       | Encryption for data in transit (HTTPS)                 |
| DNS security                  | DNSSEC for integrity; DoH/DoT for privacy              |
| Network attacks (MITM,        | Intercepting or replaying network traffic              |
|   replay, etc.)               |                                                        |
| SDN                           | Software-defined networking — programmatic control     |
| Microsegmentation             | Granular access rules between individual workloads     |

══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
DOMAIN 5: Identity & Access Management → (YOUR BACKGROUND)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

| CISSP Concept                  | Your Analogy                                          |
|-------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Authentication                | Proving who you are (password, key, biometric)         |
| Authorization                 | What you are allowed to do once authenticated          |
| Accountability                | Audit logs — who did what, when                        |
| SSO                           | One login grants access to multiple systems            |
| MFA                           | Two or more different factor types required             |
| RBAC                          | Access based on role / group membership                |
| MAC (Mandatory Access         | System enforces policy — user cannot override          |
|   Control)                    |                                                        |
| DAC (Discretionary Access     | Owner decides who gets access                          |
|   Control)                    |                                                        |
| ABAC                          | Access based on attributes (tags, context, time)       |
| Federation                    | Trust across organizational boundaries (OAuth, SAML)   |
| Identity lifecycle            | Provisioning, review, deprovisioning of accounts       |
| Privilege escalation          | Gaining higher access than intended                    |

══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
DOMAIN 6: Security Assessment & Testing → (YOUR BACKGROUND)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

| CISSP Concept                  | Your Analogy                                          |
|-------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Vulnerability scanning        | Automated scan to find known weaknesses                |
| Penetration testing           | Authorized simulated attack to test defenses           |
| Log review / audit            | Reviewing logs and dashboards for anomalies            |
| SOC 2 / audit reports         | Third-party assurance that controls are working        |
| Code review                   | Catching flaws before they reach production            |
| Synthetic transactions        | Health checks / uptime monitoring                      |
| KPIs and metrics              | Measuring security posture quantitatively              |

══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
DOMAIN 7: Security Operations → (YOUR BACKGROUND)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

| CISSP Concept                  | Your Analogy                                          |
|-------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Incident response phases      | Detection → Response → Mitigation → Reporting →       |
|                               |   Recovery → Remediation → Lessons Learned             |
| Chain of custody              | Maintaining evidence integrity for legal admissibility |
| Forensics                     | Image the disk first — never write to the original     |
| Disaster recovery             | Failover to alternate site / restore from backup       |
| RPO / RTO                     | RPO = tolerable data loss (last backup interval)       |
|                               | RTO = tolerable downtime (recovery time target)        |
| Change management             | Nothing goes to production without approval + testing  |
| Patch management              | Controlled, timely application of updates              |
| SIEM                          | Centralized log aggregation, correlation, alerting     |
| IDS/IPS                       | Detect (IDS) or block (IPS) malicious traffic          |
| DLP                           | Preventing sensitive data from leaving the network     |

══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
DOMAIN 8: Software Development Security → (YOUR BACKGROUND)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

| CISSP Concept                  | Your Analogy                                          |
|-------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| SDLC                          | Structured phases: plan → develop → test → deploy →   |
|                               |   maintain                                             |
| Secure coding practices       | Input validation, parameterized queries, output        |
|                               |   encoding                                             |
| OWASP Top 10                  | Most common web application security risks             |
| SQL injection                 | Unsanitized input executed by the database             |
| XSS                           | Malicious script injected into a web page              |
| API security                  | Authentication, rate limiting, input validation on     |
|                               |   API endpoints                                        |
| DevSecOps                     | Security scanning integrated into the development      |
|                               |   pipeline, not added after                             |
| Software supply chain         | Verifying trust in third-party code and dependencies   |
| SAST / DAST                   | SAST = scan code before it runs (static)               |
|                               | DAST = scan the running application (dynamic)          |
